#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><title>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:24
msgid "TicketIndexModule"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:26
msgid "There are two backend modules for the ticket index:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para><itemizedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:34
msgid "Kernel::System::Ticket::IndexAccelerator::RuntimeDB (default), generate each queue view on the fly from the ticket table. You will not have performance trouble until you have about 60,000 tickets (with 6,000 open tickets) in your system."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para><itemizedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:42
msgid "Kernel::System::Ticket::IndexAccelerator::StaticDB, the most powerful module, it should be used when you have above 80,000 tickets (more than 6,000 open tickets) - it use an extra ticket_index table, which works like a view. Use <filename>bin/otrs.RebuildTicketIndex.pl</filename> for generating an initial index build after switching backends."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:54
msgid "You can change the IndexAccelerator via SysConfig."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><title>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:61
msgid "TicketStorageModule"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:63
msgid "There are two different backend modules for the ticket/article storage:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para><itemizedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:71
msgid "Kernel::System::Ticket::ArticleStorageDB (default), store attachments, etc.  in the database. Note: Don't use it for large set ups."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para><itemizedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:75
msgid "Pro: If your webserver user isn't the otrs user, use this module to avoid file permission problems."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para><itemizedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:79
msgid "Contra: It's not really advisable to store attachments in your database. Take care that your database is able to store large objects. E.g. MySQL (config)  \"set-variable = max_allowed_packet=8M\" to store 8 MB objects (default is 2M)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para><itemizedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:87
msgid "Kernel::System::Ticket::ArticleStorageFS, store attachments etc. on the local file system. Note: Recommended for large setups."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para><itemizedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:91
msgid "Pro: Fast!"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para><itemizedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:94
msgid "Contra: Your web server user should be the otrs user (file system permissions!).  Also, if you have multiple front end servers, you should make sure the file system is shared between the servers. So place it on an NFS share or preferably a SAN or similar solution."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:106
msgid "Note: you can switch from one to the other back-end on the fly. You can switch the backend in the SysConfig, and then you can run the command line utility <filename>otrs.ArticleStorageSwitch.pl</filename> to put the articles from the database onto the filesystem or the other way around. You can use the <emphasis>-s</emphasis> and <emphasis>-d</emphasis> option to specify the source and destination back-ends. Please note that the whole process can take a lot of time, depending on the amount of articles you have and the available CPU power and/or network capacity."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para><programlisting>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:118
#, no-wrap
msgid "shell> bin/otrs.ArticleStorageSwitch.pl -s ArticleStorageDB -d ArticleStorageFS\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:122
msgid "<emphasis>Script 21.1 Switching storage back-ends from database to filesystem.</emphasis>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><title>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:127
msgid "Archiving Tickets"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:130
msgid "As OTRS can be used as an audit proof system, deleting closed tickets may not be a good idea.  Therefore we implemented a feature that allows you to archive tickets."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:134
msgid "This means that tickets that match certain criteria are marked as \"archived\", and these tickets are not touched if you do a regular ticket search or run a Generic Agent job.  The system itself has not to deal with a huge amount of tickets any longer as only the \"latest\" tickets are taken into consideration when using OTRS. This can mean a huge performance gain on large systems."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:141
msgid "To use the archive feature simply follow these steps:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><orderedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:146
msgid "Activate the archive system in SysConfig"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><orderedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:149
msgid "In the Admin panel of OTRS go to SysConfig and select the group <literal>Ticket</literal>.  In <literal>Core::Ticket</literal> you find the option <literal>Ticket::ArchiveSystem</literal> which is set to \"no\" per default. Change this setting to \"yes\" and save this change."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><orderedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:156
